data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for your scenarios:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0); // or:
    CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(users); // MSTest v3+

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)); // no built-in predicate version

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a == b)` | `Assert.AreEqual(a, b)` |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` ‚Äî item exists
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)` ‚Äî no duplicates
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)` ‚Äî containment
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` ‚Äî same items, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` ‚Äî same items, same order

The main benefit: when tests fail, these give specific messages (e.g., "Expected: 3, Actual: 0") instead of just "Assert.IsTrue failed."
